> writing (and privacy, ha) has always been part of my life.
>
> Around 2010, I decided I wanted to give digital products a go. Web design
> was going well, but I wanted something different. No idea why, I just
> craved a change, challenge and something new.
>
> So I started writing more. I wrote a couple books and self-published them=
.
> They sold well enough that they earned some money. I wrote some articles
> that got picked up by publications, and people started paying attention
> with their minds and wallets to the things I was saying and selling.
>
> I started this list in November 2013. I began and still continue to write
> an article (or some grouping of words) every Sunday, without missing a
> week, unless I=E2=80=99m on a scheduled break (summers and December, most=
ly).
>
> It took almost three years, but I transitioned my income completely from
> client work to product work. The idea I was working towards was that I=E2=
=80=99d
> stop doing client work if my product income became higher than my freelan=
ce
> income, despite spending fewer hours on products. So I had to make more a=
nd
> work less, otherwise I wouldn=E2=80=99t make the switch. Luckily, I suppo=
se, that
> happened around the release of my third book. I still actually miss clien=
t
> work sometimes, as in some ways it feels easier to have 12 or so clients =
a
> year versus thousands of customers.
>
> Then, as writing started to take shape for me, I got pretty heavy into
> making online courses. I created seven or eight over six years, and two a=
re
> still going strong. The rest I axed because they weren=E2=80=99t selling =
